## Architecture

```
CloudFront (${{ values.awsRegion }})
  ├── /*         → S3 bucket (Next.js static export)
  └── /api/*     → API Gateway HTTP API → Lambda → DynamoDB (${{ values.tableName }})
```

No CORS configuration needed — CloudFront proxies all traffic under a single domain.

## Local Development

### Prerequisites

- Node.js 20+
- AWS credentials configured (for Lambda dev/test)

### Run the frontend

```bash
npm install --registry=https://registry.npmjs.org/
npm run dev
```

The Next.js dev server starts at `http://localhost:3000`.

### Lambda local testing

You can invoke the Lambda handler directly with a mock event:

```js
import { handler } from './lambda/index.mjs'

const event = {
  requestContext: { http: { method: 'GET', path: '/api/items' } },
}

console.log(await handler(event))
```

Set `TABLE_NAME` environment variable to your DynamoDB table name.

## Deployment

Push to `main` — the GitHub Actions workflow will:

1. Run `terraform apply` to provision/update AWS resources
2. Build the Next.js app (`next build`) and sync the `out/` export to S3
3. Invalidate the CloudFront cache
4. Deploy the Lambda function

### Required GitHub secret

| Secret | Description |
|--------|-------------|
| `AWS_DEPLOY_ROLE_ARN` | IAM role ARN with permissions to deploy all resources |

## Infrastructure

All infrastructure is defined in `terraform/`:

| File | Contents |
|------|----------|
| `providers.tf` | AWS + archive providers |
| `backend.tf` | S3 remote state backend |
| `variables.tf` | Input variables |
| `main.tf` | All resources (S3, CloudFront, API GW, Lambda, DynamoDB, IAM) |
| `outputs.tf` | CloudFront domain, S3 bucket, table name, etc. |
